Because the DatatableView need to provide its own configuration details, ``datatableview.initialize(".datatable")`` will actually perform the whole javascript init process, and allows you to pass your mapping of options as the second arg.

We dump some configuration options into the table DOM as ``data-*`` attributes that will be read by `datatableview.initialize()`` to build a starting point of options, and then any additional options supplied by the second arg will trump those:

```javascript
datatableview.auto_initialize = false;
$(document).ready(function(){
    datatableview.initialize($(".datatable"), {
        initComplete: function(){
            var api = this.api();
            // ...
        }
    });
```

So the ``initComplete`` should be sent to our init helper by nature of the fact that it's building the options it intends to send to the real dataTables.js constructor.  You should be able to completely avoid calling the vanilla constructor yourself, as this might produce some unexpected results.

