I agree for model loading over shared memory. Let's consider that as soon as you startup your model like:

```javascript
var fastText = new FastText({
    serializeTo: './band_model',
    trainFile: './band_train.txt'
});

fastText.train()
.then(done=> {
    console.log("train done.");
})
.catch(error => {
    console.error(error);
})
```

the `fastText` instance keeps the model loaded so you can do inference (predict) like

```javascript
var sample="Our Twitter run by the band and crew to give you an inside look into our lives on the road. Get #FutureHearts now: http://smarturl.it/futurehearts";
fastText.load()
.then(done => {
    return fastText.predict(sample);
})
.then(labels=> {
    console.log("TEXT:", sample, "\nPREDICT:",labels );
    sample="LBi Software provides precisely engineered, customer-focused #HRTECH solutions. Our flagship solution, LBi HR HelpDesk, is a SaaS #HR Case Management product.";
    return fastText.predict(sample);
})
.then(labels=> {
    console.log("TEXT:", sample, "\nPREDICT:",labels );
    fastText.unload();
})
.catch(error => {
    console.error(error);
});
```

in your running web service instance. See [fasttext.js](https://github.com/loretoparisi/fasttext.js) for more details

I think this makes sense. If a normal property getter receives the instance as the implicit 'self' reference, then it should be the 'type' subclass instance for a static property getter.

If you take a look at the implementation of ``def_readonly_static``, you can see that it actually takes a py::object in the lambda function that acts as the property getter:
```c++
    template <typename D, typename... Extra>
    class_ &def_readonly_static(const char *name, const D *pm, const Extra& ...extra) {
        cpp_function fget([pm](object) -> const D &{ return *pm; }, scope(*this));
        def_property_readonly_static(name, fget, return_value_policy::reference, extra...);
        return *this;
    }
```
This could be a bit more explicit in the documentation though -- I will add a note.

